Actually, my primary problem with xp was not lack of multi-group xp (although I agree they should implement this).  My chief complaint is that mob xp is based solely on the level of the mob.  Mobs that have more hps, or extra abilities, should be worth more xp than a mob of the same level with average hps and no extra abilities.  This is common sense, yet for some reason VI just hasn't implemented it this way.<br>
<br>
2nd edition D&amp;D Monster Manual had rules for designing your own monsters.  For each ability you gave, it added to the base xp cost for that creature.  If you gave a level 10 monster all these special abilities, it became worth much more xp.<br>
<br>
So many mobs in EQ are not killed by anyone just because they have more hit points than the average mob of their level.  Why should someone spend more time killing these mobs for the same xp when they can go kill mobs with fewer hps?  With a modified xp system, where xp rewarded actually corresponded to the mob difficulty, many more mobs would be killed.<br>
<br>
I'm not the first to complain about this problem, and I doubt I'll be the last.<br>
<br>
